![](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d56e145f80b7500016ba502/9e08fd1b-6f12-462e-bba5-9e20f7961e59/processed_9200.jpg)

An unexpected announcement from WWE is set to ignite a new chapter in the company's rivalry with All Elite Wrestling. It has been reported that the planned main event for WWE's yet-to-be-announced premium live event on September 20 is a major clash between Brock Lesnar and John Cena. This event is scheduled to air head-to-head with AEW's All Out pay-per-view.

The strategic booking of Lesnar versus Cena is reportedly the reason for Lesnar's absence from the upcoming "Clash in Paris" event. Sources indicate that WWE prioritized Lesnar for this specific date as a direct method of counter-programming AEW. The move to schedule a main roster PLE on the same night as an AEW pay-per-view marks a significant escalation in their competitive tactics. Previously, the companies had squared off with WWE's developmental brand, NXT, against AEW's major events, such as NXT Battleground against AEW Double or Nothing, and NXT Great American Bash against AEW All In: Texas.

The strategy behind counter-programming is to dominate the online conversation and social media space on a night when a rival company is holding a major event. While some believe this move will only intensify the loyalty of AEW's hardcore fanbase, others contend that a marquee match-up like Lesnar vs. Cena will capture the attention of a broader, more casual audience, thereby diverting mindshare from AEW's product.

This latest booking decision suggests that WWE, under its TKO-led management, intends to continue this competitive approach.